{
  "In quantum mechanics, a qubit state is represented as |psi> = a|0> + b|1>. What constraint must |a|^2 + |b|^2 satisfy?": "",
  "It can be any positive number": "",
  "It must equal 0": "",
  "It must equal 1": "",
  "It must be less than 1": "",
  "Quantum states must be normalized: the sum of the squared magnitudes of the amplitudes must equal 1, ensuring total probability of all measurement outcomes is 100%.": "",
  "The Pauli-X matrix is X = [[0,1],[1,0]]. What is X applied to the state |0> = [1,0]^T?": "",
  "[0,1]^T = |1>": "",
  "[0,0]^T": "",
  "[1,1]^T": "",
  "[1,0]^T = |0>": "",
  "X|0> = [[0,1],[1,0]] * [1,0]^T = [0*1+1*0, 1*1+0*0]^T = [0,1]^T = |1>. The Pauli-X gate acts as a quantum NOT gate, flipping |0> to |1>.": "",
  "What are the eigenvalues of the Pauli-Z matrix Z = [[1,0],[0,-1]]?": "",
  "1 and 1": "",
  "0 and 1": "",
  "i and -i": "",
  "1 and -1": "",
  "The Pauli-Z matrix is already diagonal, so its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries: 1 and -1. The eigenstates are |0> (eigenvalue +1) and |1> (eigenvalue -1).": "",
  "A spin-1/2 particle has the Hamiltonian H = [[3,0],[0,-3]] (in units of hbar*omega). What are the energy eigenvalues?": "",
  "3 and 3": "",
  "9 and -9": "",
  "3 and -3": "",
  "0 and 6": "",
  "Since H is diagonal, the eigenvalues are the diagonal entries: 3 and -3 (in units of hbar*omega). These represent the two possible energy levels of the spin-1/2 system.": "",
  "The tensor product of |0> = [1,0]^T and |1> = [0,1]^T gives the 2-qubit state |01>. What is this tensor product as a 4-dimensional vector?": "",
  "[1,0,1,0]^T": "",
  "[0,1,0,0]^T": "",
  "[0,0,1,0]^T": "",
  "[1,0,0,1]^T": "",
  "|0> tensor |1> = [1,0]^T tensor [0,1]^T = [1*[0,1], 0*[0,1]]^T = [0,1,0,0]^T. This is the standard computational basis state |01> in the 4-dimensional Hilbert space.": "",
  "A quantum observable is represented by a Hermitian matrix. What property do the eigenvalues of a Hermitian matrix always have?": "",
  "They are all positive": "",
  "They are all complex": "",
  "They always come in pairs": "",
  "They are all real numbers": "",
  "Hermitian matrices (A = A^dagger) always have real eigenvalues. This is essential in quantum mechanics because eigenvalues represent measurement outcomes, which must be real numbers.": "",
  "The Hadamard gate is H = (1/sqrt(2))*[[1,1],[1,-1]]. What is H|0>?": "",
  "(1/sqrt(2))(|0> + |1>)": "",
  "|0>": "",
  "|1>": "",
  "(1/sqrt(2))(|0> - |1>)": "",
  "H|0> = (1/sqrt(2))*[[1,1],[1,-1]]*[1,0]^T = (1/sqrt(2))*[1,1]^T = (1/sqrt(2))(|0> + |1>). The Hadamard gate creates an equal superposition from a basis state.": "",
  "In quantum mechanics, what is the probability of measuring eigenvalue lambda if the system is in state |psi> and the observable has eigenvector |lambda>?": "",
  "<psi|lambda> + <lambda|psi>": "",
  "|<lambda|psi>|^2": "",
  "lambda * <psi|psi>": "",
  "<lambda|psi>": "",
  "Born's rule states that the probability of measuring eigenvalue lambda is the squared magnitude of the inner product of the eigenvector with the state: P(lambda) = |<lambda|psi>|^2.": "",
  "A unitary matrix U satisfies U^dagger * U = I. What does this imply about |det(U)|?": "",
  "|det(U)| = 1": "",
  "|det(U)| > 1": "",
  "det(U) = 0": "",
  "det(U) must be real": "",
  "From U^dagger U = I, taking determinants: det(U^dagger)*det(U) = 1. Since det(U^dagger) = conj(det(U)), we get |det(U)|^2 = 1, so |det(U)| = 1.": "",
  "The density matrix of a pure state |psi> = [1/sqrt(2), 1/sqrt(2)]^T is rho = |psi><psi|. What is rho?": "",
  "[[1/2, 1/2],[1/2, 1/2]]": "",
  "[[1, 0],[0, 1]]": "",
  "[[1, 1],[1, 1]]": "",
  "[[1/2, 0],[0, 1/2]]": "",
  "rho = |psi><psi| = [1/sqrt(2), 1/sqrt(2)]^T * [1/sqrt(2), 1/sqrt(2)] = [[1/2, 1/2],[1/2, 1/2]]. Note tr(rho) = 1 and rho^2 = rho, confirming it is a pure state.": "",
  "What is a 'Hilbert space' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A 3-dimensional physical space where quantum experiments are conducted": "",
  "A complete inner product space that serves as the mathematical framework for quantum states": "",
  "A type of vector space that only contains real-valued vectors": "",
  "The space of all possible measurement outcomes": "",
  "A Hilbert space is a complete vector space equipped with an inner product. In quantum mechanics, quantum states are vectors (or rays) in a Hilbert space, and the inner product defines probabilities and expectation values.": "",
  "What does 'unitary operator' mean in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "An operator U satisfying U^dagger U = UU^dagger = I, representing reversible quantum evolution": "",
  "Any operator that acts on a single qubit": "",
  "An operator that maps all states to a single state": "",
  "An operator with exactly one eigenvalue": "",
  "A unitary operator preserves inner products and norms, meaning it preserves probability. All quantum gates and time-evolution operators (in closed systems) are unitary, ensuring reversibility and probability conservation.": "",
  "What is 'superposition' in terms of linear algebra?": "",
  "A quantum state expressed as a linear combination of basis vectors with complex coefficients": "",
  "The largest eigenvalue of a quantum observable": "",
  "A state that exists in multiple physical locations simultaneously": "",
  "The process of multiplying two quantum states together": "",
  "Superposition is the fundamental principle that quantum states can be linear combinations of basis states: |psi> = c1|v1> + c2|v2> + ... This is directly the concept of a linear combination from linear algebra.": "",
  "What does 'entanglement' mean in the context of tensor products?": "",
  "A multi-particle quantum state that cannot be written as a tensor product of individual particle states": "",
  "Any state in a tensor product space": "",
  "A state where all particles have the same quantum numbers": "",
  "The tensor product of two identical states": "",
  "An entangled state like (|00> + |11>)/sqrt(2) cannot be decomposed as |a> tensor |b> for any single-qubit states |a> and |b>. Entanglement represents non-classical correlations between subsystems.": "",
  "What is a 'density matrix' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A diagonal matrix of quantum numbers": "",
  "A matrix containing the mass density of quantum particles": "",
  "The probability distribution of eigenvalues": "",
  "A positive semi-definite Hermitian matrix with trace 1 that generalizes the state vector to describe both pure and mixed quantum states": "",
  "The density matrix rho is a Hermitian, positive semi-definite matrix with tr(rho) = 1. For a pure state, rho = |psi><psi| with rho^2 = rho. For mixed states, rho = sum p_i |psi_i><psi_i| describes statistical mixtures.": "",
  "What does 'expectation value' of an observable mean in quantum linear algebra?": "",
  "The determinant of the observable matrix": "",
  "The largest eigenvalue of the observable A": "",
  "<A> = <psi|A|psi>, the average measurement outcome of observable A in state |psi>": "",
  "The most likely measurement outcome": "",
  "The expectation value <A> = <psi|A|psi> gives the statistical average of many measurements of observable A on identically prepared systems in state |psi>. It is computed as a matrix-vector product using the inner product.": "",
  "What is a 'projection operator' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "An operator P satisfying P^2 = P and P = P^dagger that projects states onto a subspace": "",
  "The inverse of a unitary operator": "",
  "An operator that rotates quantum states by 90 degrees": "",
  "Any operator that reduces the dimension of the Hilbert space": "",
  "A projection operator P is both idempotent (P^2 = P) and Hermitian (P = P^dagger). It projects any state onto a particular subspace, and is used to describe quantum measurements.": "",
  "What does 'spectral decomposition' mean for a quantum observable?": "",
  "Writing the observable as A = sum lambda_i |i><i|, decomposing it into eigenvalues and eigenprojectors": "",
  "Splitting the observable into its real and imaginary parts": "",
  "Measuring the frequency spectrum of a quantum system": "",
  "Diagonalizing the density matrix": "",
  "The spectral theorem states that any Hermitian operator A can be written as A = sum lambda_i P_i, where lambda_i are eigenvalues and P_i = |i><i| are projection operators onto the corresponding eigenspaces.": "",
  "What is 'decoherence' in terms of density matrices?": "",
  "The transition from a mixed state to a pure state": "",
  "The process by which off-diagonal elements of the density matrix decay toward zero, turning a pure state into a mixed state": "",
  "When all eigenvalues of the density matrix become equal": "",
  "When the density matrix becomes the zero matrix": "",
  "Decoherence occurs when a quantum system interacts with its environment, causing the off-diagonal elements of the density matrix (which represent quantum coherence/superposition) to decay, effectively transitioning the system from a pure superposition to a classical-like mixed state.": "",
  "What does 'commutator' mean for two quantum operators A and B?": "",
  "AB + BA, the sum of operator products": "",
  "[A,B] = AB - BA, measuring how much A and B fail to commute": "",
  "The tensor product of A and B": "",
  "The trace of A times B": "",
  "The commutator [A,B] = AB - BA quantifies the degree to which two operators fail to commute. If [A,B] = 0, the operators commute and share simultaneous eigenstates. Non-zero commutators lead to uncertainty relations.": "",
  "A physicist prepares a qubit in state |psi> = (3/5)|0> + (4/5)|1> and measures in the computational basis. What is the probability of measuring |0>?": "",
  "16/25": "",
  "4/5": "",
  "3/5": "",
  "9/25": "",
  "By Born's rule, P(|0>) = |<0|psi>|^2 = |3/5|^2 = 9/25 = 0.36. Note: |3/5|^2 + |4/5|^2 = 9/25 + 16/25 = 25/25 = 1, confirming normalization.": "",
  "A quantum computing researcher applies the Pauli-Y gate Y = [[0,-i],[i,0]] to the state |1> = [0,1]^T. What is the resulting state?": "",
  "|1> = [0, 1]^T": "",
  "i|0> = [i, 0]^T": "",
